      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Material properties and geometric inputs sourced from calibrated measurements with stated uncertainty; sensitivity analysis performed for key inputs.",
      "rationale": "Titanium alloy material properties obtained from coupon testing of the same material lot as the test constructs. Screw and rod geometry digitized from CMM measurements. One-at-a-time sensitivity analysis confirms stiffness QoI is most sensitive to rod modulus (±3% effect per ±5% input variation)."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "N ≥ 10 constructs with documented traceability to production-representative hardware; inter-laboratory consistency confirmed.",
      "rationale": "N=11 non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screw constructs tested across two independent laboratories. All constructs are production-representative hardware from the same manufacturing lot. Inter-laboratory coefficient of variation for stiffness is 3.1%, within acceptable limits."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 1,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Test conditions span the range of clinically relevant loading scenarios including at least two distinct load magnitudes or configurations to characterize model response across the COU envelope.",
      "rationale": "Testing was conducted strictly per ASTM F1717 standard protocol, which specifies a single fixed compressive offset load configuration. The experimental program was well-controlled and reproducible across both laboratories, with load cell calibration traceable to NIST standards. The standardized test method is widely accepted by FDA for 510(k) submissions and provides a consistent benchmark for model comparison. Engineering judgment supports that the ASTM F1717 configuration is representative of worst-case compression-bending in clinical use."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Documented mapping between experimental boundary conditions and FEA boundary conditions; any deviations quantified and their effect on QoI estimated.",
      "rationale": "FEA boundary conditions directly replicate the ASTM F1717 fixture geometry, load application point, and constraint configuration. The 10 mm offset distance and loading axis alignment are implemented to within 0.1 mm of the fixture drawings. No significant deviations identified."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Quantitative comparison metric (E/uval) applied to all three QoIs; all E/uval < 1.96 at 95% confidence.",
      "rationale": "E/uval computed for stiffness (0.87), yield force (1.42), and force at 40 mm (1.61). All three values are below the 1.96 threshold. Percent differences are 4.2%, 6.8%, and 7.3% respectively, all within the 10% acceptance bound. Validation is quantitatively successful across all QoIs."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "QoIs (stiffness, yield force, force at 40 mm displacement) are directly linked to clinical failure modes and FDA submission requirements for spinal implants.",
      "rationale": "The three QoIs are the primary metrics specified in ASTM F1717 and directly correspond to construct mechanical performance endpoints relevant to FDA 510(k) review. Stiffness characterizes load transfer; yield force and force at 40 mm bound the failure envelope. QoI relevance is well-established."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "The validation scenario (ASTM F1717 non-cannulated 7.5 mm construct) is sufficiently similar to the intended COU that extrapolation uncertainty is minimal.",
      "rationale": "The validation activity is identical to the COU: the same hardware, same test standard, same loading configuration, and same QoIs. No extrapolation is required. The validation scenario directly supports the COU without reliance on surrogate geometries or loading conditions."
